# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: databricks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Apache Spark has its architectural foundation in the resilient distributed dataset (RDD), a read-only multiset of data items distributed over a cluster of machines, that is maintained in a fault-tolerant way.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The Dataframe API was released as an abstraction on top of the RDD, followed by the Dataset API.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] In Spark 1.x, the RDD was the primary application programming interface (API), but as of Spark 2.x use of the Dataset API is encouraged even though the RDD API is not deprecated.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The RDD technology still underlies the Dataset API.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark's RDDs function as a working set for distributed programs that offers a (deliberately) restricted form of distributed shared memory.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Inside Apache Spark the workflow is managed as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Nodes represent RDDs while edges represent the operations on the RDDs.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark facilitates the implementation of both iterative algorithms, which visit their data set multiple times in a loop, and interactive/exploratory data analysis, i.e., the repeated database-style querying of data.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The latency of such applications may be reduced by several orders of magnitude compared to Apache Hadoop MapReduce implementation.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Among the class of iterative algorithms are the training algorithms for machine learning systems, which formed the initial impetus for developing Apache Spark.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Apache Spark requires a cluster manager and a distributed storage system.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] For cluster management, Spark supports standalone native Spark, Hadoop YARN, Apache Mesos or Kubernetes.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] A standalone native Spark cluster can be launched manually or by the launch scripts provided by the install package.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] It is also possible to run the daemons on a single machine for testing.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] For distributed storage Spark can interface with a wide variety of distributed systems, including Alluxio, Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), MapR File System (MapR-FS), Cassandra, OpenStack Swift, Amazon S3, Kudu, Lustre file system, or a custom solution can be implemented.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark also supports a pseudo-distributed local mode, usually used only for development or testing purposes, where distributed storage is not required and the local file system can be used instead; in such a scenario, Spark is run on a single machine with one executor per CPU core.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark Core is the foundation of the overall project.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] This interface mirrors a functional/higher-order model of programming: a "driver" program invokes parallel operations such as map, filter or reduce on an RDD by passing a function to Spark, which then schedules the function's execution in parallel on the cluster.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] These operations, and additional ones such as joins, take RDDs as input and produce new RDDs.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] RDDs are immutable and their operations are lazy; fault-tolerance is achieved by keeping track of the "lineage" of each RDD (the sequence of operations that produced it) so that it can be reconstructed in the case of data loss.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] RDDs can contain any type of Python, .NET, Java, or Scala objects.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Besides the RDD-oriented functional style of programming, Spark provides two restricted forms of shared variables: *broadcast variables* reference read-only data that needs to be available on all nodes, while *accumulators* can be used to program reductions in an imperative style.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] A typical example of RDD-centric functional programming is the following Scala program that computes the frequencies of all words occurring in a set of text files and prints the most common ones.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Each map, flatMap (a variant of map) and reduceByKey takes an anonymous function that performs a simple operation on a single data item (or a pair of items), and applies its argument to transform an RDD into a new RDD.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] PySpark is the Python API for Apache Spark, introduced in Spark 0.7, released in February 2013.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] It allows Spark applications to be written in Python and provides an interactive shell for exploratory analysis.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] PySpark code executes under the standard CPython runtime and can call native Python libraries such as NumPy and SciPy; communication between Python user code and Spark's JVM-based core has historically been mediated by the Py4J library.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] PySpark provides Python interfaces to most of Spark's components, including Spark Core, Spark SQL and the DataFrame API, Structured Streaming, and MLlib; since Spark 4.1 it also exposes the Spark Declarative Pipelines API.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] A pandas-compatible API, known as *pandas API on Spark*, was integrated into PySpark in Apache Spark 3.2.0, released in October 2021.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] It provides equivalents to the pandas data-analysis API that execute against the Spark engine, allowing pandas-style code to be run on distributed data.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The component originated as Koalas, a separate project open-sourced by Databricks in 2019, which was subsequently merged into PySpark.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] PySpark also provides a client for Spark Connect, a client–server architecture that enables remote connectivity to Spark clusters from PySpark applications.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark SQL is a component on top of Spark Core that introduced a data abstraction called DataFrames, which provides support for structured and semi-structured data.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark SQL provides a domain-specific language (DSL) to manipulate DataFrames in Scala, Java, Python or .NET.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] It also provides SQL language support, with command-line interfaces and ODBC/JDBC server.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Although DataFrames lack the compile-time type-checking afforded by RDDs, as of Spark 2.0, the strongly typed DataSet is fully supported by Spark SQL as well.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark Declarative Pipelines (SDP) is a declarative framework for defining and running extract, transform, load (ETL) data pipelines, added in Apache Spark 4.1.0, which was released on December 16, 2025.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Developers declare the datasets a pipeline should produce and the queries that define them, rather than writing imperative code specifying how each dataset is computed and in what order; Spark constructs a dataflow graph and manages dependency ordering, parallelism, checkpointing, and retries.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The framework extends Spark's lazy, declarative execution model, previously applied to individual queries through Spark SQL, to pipelines spanning multiple datasets.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Pipelines are defined in SQL or Python and are organized around streaming tables and materialized views, with the underlying transformations expressed as "flows"; batch and streaming computations can be combined within a single pipeline.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark Structured Streaming uses Spark Core's fast scheduling capability to perform streaming analytics.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] It ingests data in micro-batches and performs RDD transformations on those micro-batches of data.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] This design enables the same set of application code written for batch analytics to be used in streaming analytics, thus facilitating easy implementation of lambda architecture.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] However, this convenience comes with the penalty of latency equal to the mini-batch duration.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Other streaming data engines that process event by event rather than in micro-batches include Storm and the streaming component of Flink.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark Streaming has support built-in to consume from Kafka, Flume, Twitter, ZeroMQ, Kinesis, and TCP/IP sockets.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] In Spark 2.x, a separate technology based on Datasets, called Structured Streaming, that has a higher-level interface is also provided to support streaming.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Apache Spark 4.x added a Real-Time Mode (RTM) execution model for Structured Streaming, with the stated goal of lowering end-to-end latency to support operational and batch workloads on a single engine.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Existing Structured Streaming queries written against the DataFrame and Dataset APIs can be executed under the new mode without modification to the query.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark can be deployed in a traditional on-premises data center as well as in the cloud.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark Connect is a decoupled client–server architecture for Apache Spark that allows remote applications to connect to a Spark cluster from any environment, introduced in Apache Spark 3.4, released in April 2023.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The architecture separates the client application from the Spark driver, which historically ran in the same process; under Spark Connect, the client is a thin library that can be embedded in application servers, IDEs, notebooks and other programming environments.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Results are streamed back to the client as Apache Arrow-encoded row batches.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] PySpark support for Spark Connect was added in Spark 3.4, and Scala client support followed in Spark 3.5; additional clients for languages including Go, Swift and Rust have been developed in later releases.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] GraphX is a distributed graph-processing framework on top of Apache Spark.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Because it is based on RDDs, which are immutable, graphs are immutable and thus GraphX is unsuitable for graphs that need to be updated, let alone in a transactional manner like a graph database.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] GraphX provides two separate APIs for implementation of massively parallel algorithms (such as PageRank): a Pregel abstraction, and a more general MapReduce-style API.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Unlike its predecessor Bagel, which was formally deprecated in Spark 1.6, GraphX has full support for property graphs (graphs where properties can be attached to edges and vertices).
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Like Apache Spark, GraphX initially started as a research project at UC Berkeley's AMPLab and Databricks, and was later donated to the Apache Software Foundation and the Spark project.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Apache Spark has built-in support for Scala, Java, SQL, R, Python, and Swift with 3rd party support for the .NET CLR, Julia, and more.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark was initially started by Matei Zaharia at UC Berkeley's AMPLab in 2009, and open sourced in 2010 under a BSD license.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] In 2013, the project was donated to the Apache Software Foundation and switched its license to Apache 2.0.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] In February 2014, Spark became a Top-Level Apache Project.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Zaharia's company Databricks set a new world record in large scale sorting using Spark.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark had in excess of 1000 contributors in 2015, making it one of the most active projects in the Apache Software Foundation and one of the most active open source big data projects.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Spark 3.5.2 is based on Scala 2.13 (and thus works with Scala 2.12 and 2.13 out-of-the-box), but it can also be made to work with Scala 3.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Apache Spark is developed by a community.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The project is managed by a group called the "Project Management Committee" (PMC).
[src:databricks/apache-spark] Feature release branches will, generally, be maintained with bug fix releases for a period of 18 months.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] For example, branch 2.3.x is no longer considered maintained as of September 2019, 18 months after the release of 2.3.0 in February 2018.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] No more 2.3.x releases should be expected after that point, even for bug fixes.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] The last minor release within a major a release will typically be maintained for longer as an “LTS” release.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] For example, 2.4.0 was released on November 2, 2018, and had been maintained for 31 months until 2.4.8 was released in May 2021.
[src:databricks/apache-spark] 2.4.8 is the last release and no more 2.4.x releases should be expected even for bug fixes.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] BI tools can handle large amounts of structured and sometimes unstructured data to help organizations identify, develop, and otherwise create new strategic business opportunities.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] They aim to allow for the easy interpretation of these big data.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Identifying new opportunities and implementing an effective strategy based on insights is assumed to potentially provide businesses with a competitive market advantage and long-term stability, and help them take strategic decisions.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Business intelligence can be used by enterprises to support a wide range of business decisions ranging from operational to strategic.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Basic operating decisions include product positioning or pricing.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Strategic business decisions involve priorities, goals, and directions at the broadest level.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] In all cases, business intelligence is considered most effective when it combines data from the market in which a company operates (external data) with data from internal company sources, such as financial and operational information.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] When integrated, external and internal data provide a comprehensive view that creates ‘intelligence’ not possible from any single data source alone.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Among their many uses, business intelligence tools empower organizations to gain insight into new markets, to assess demand and suitability of products and services for different market segments, and to gauge the impact of marketing efforts.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] BI applications use data gathered from a data warehouse (DW) or from a data mart, and the concepts of BI and DW combine as "BI/DW" or as "BIDW".
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] A data warehouse contains a copy of analytical data that facilitates decision support.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] The earliest known use of the term *business intelligence* is in Richard Millar Devens' *Cyclopædia of Commercial and Business Anecdotes* (1865).
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] The ability to collect and react accordingly based on the information retrieved, Devens says, is central to business intelligence.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] In 1989, Howard Dresner (later a Gartner analyst) proposed *business intelligence* as an umbrella term to describe "concepts and methods to improve business decision making by using fact-based support systems." It was not until the late 1990s that this usage was widespread.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Therefore, Forrester refers to *data preparation* and *data usage* as two separate but closely linked segments of the business-intelligence architectural stack.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] If understood broadly, competitive intelligence can be considered as a subset of business intelligence.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Business intelligence and business analytics are sometimes used interchangeably, but there are alternate definitions.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Thomas Davenport, professor of information technology and management at Babson College argues that business intelligence should be divided into querying, reporting, Online analytical processing (OLAP), an "alerts" tool, and business analytics.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] In this definition, business analytics is the subset of BI focusing on statistics, prediction, and optimization, rather than the reporting functionality.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Business operations can generate a very large amount of data in the form of emails, memos, notes from call centers, news, user groups, chats, reports, web pages, presentations, image files, video files, and marketing material.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] According to Merrill Lynch, more than 85% of all business information exists in these forms; a company might only use such a document a single time.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Because of the way it is produced and stored, this information is either unstructured or semi-structured.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] The management of semi-structured data is an unsolved problem in the information technology industry.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] According to projections from Gartner (2003), white-collar workers spend 30–40% of their time searching, finding, and assessing unstructured data.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] BI uses both structured and unstructured data.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] The former is easy to search, and the latter contains a large quantity of the information needed for analysis and decision-making.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Because of the difficulty of properly searching, finding, and assessing unstructured or semi-structured data, organizations may not draw upon these vast reservoirs of information, which could influence a particular decision, task, or project.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] This can ultimately lead to poorly informed decision-making.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Therefore, when designing a business intelligence/DW solution, the specific problems associated with semi-structured and unstructured data must be accommodated, as well as those associated with structured data.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] There are several challenges to developing BI with semi-structured data.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] To solve problems with searchability and assessment of data, it is necessary to know something about the content.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] This can be done by adding context through the use of metadata.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Many systems already capture some metadata (e.g. filename, author, size, etc.), but more useful would be metadata about the actual content – e.g. summaries, topics, people, or companies mentioned.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Two technologies designed for generating metadata about content are automatic categorization and information extraction.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Generative business intelligence is the application of generative AI techniques, such as large language models, in business intelligence.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] This combination facilitates data analysis and enables users to interact with data more intuitively, generating actionable insights through natural language queries.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Microsoft Copilot was, for example, integrated into the business analytics tool Power BI.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] In a 2013 report, Gartner categorized business intelligence vendors as either an independent "pure-play" vendor or a consolidated "mega-vendor".
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] In 2019, the BI market was shaken within Europe for the new legislation of GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) which puts the responsibility of data collection and storage onto the data user with strict laws in place to make sure the data is compliant.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Growth within Europe has steadily increased since May 2019 when GDPR was brought in.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] The legislation refocused companies to look at their own data from a compliance perspective but also revealed future opportunities using personalization and external BI providers to increase market share.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] A Business Intelligence Competency Center (BICC) is a team that supports the use of business intelligence in an organization.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Since 2001, the BICC concept has been refined through implementations in organizations that have adopted BI and related analytical software.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Usage of the term BICC has varied significantly across implementations in different organizations.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] The adoption of the BICC concept has led some organizations to establish units that focus on the use of BI software for decision-making, which may increase the value an organization derives from its BI implementation.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] A BICC coordinates activities and resources to facilitate a fact-based approach to decision-making within an organization.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] It has responsibility for the governance structure for BI and the use of analytical programs, projects, practices, software, and architecture.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] A BICC is responsible for developing plans, priorities, infrastructure, and competencies that can support strategic decision-making using BI and analytical software.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] In recent years, knowledge-oriented shared service centers have emerged in many organizations.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Their primary focus has been the offering of analytics and data mining as an internal service across the organization.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Such a center may be referred to as an Analytics Competency Center (ACC), Analytics Center of Excellence, Analytics Service Center, Big Data CoC, or Big Data Lab.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] By the end of 2017, a report by Gartner Research estimated that approximately 25% of large firms had a dedicated ACC unit (or equivalent) for data and analytics.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] In contrast to classic BICCs, these centers do not place emphasis on reporting, historical analysis, and dashboards.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] ACCs aim to enhance a company's data capabilities by building expertise in data analytics, formulating a data strategy, identifying use cases for data mining, and promoting the adoption of analytics within the organization.
[src:databricks/business-intelligence] Although BICCs can change into ACCs, new ACC formations can also occur in practice.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Around the 1970s/1980s the term *information engineering methodology* (IEM) was created to describe database design and the use of software for data analysis and processing.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] These techniques were intended to be used by database administrators (DBAs) and by systems analysts based upon an understanding of the operational processing needs of organizations for the 1980s.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] In particular, these techniques were meant to help bridge the gap between strategic business planning and information systems.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] A key early contributor (often called the "father" of information engineering methodology) was the Australian Clive Finkelstein, who wrote several articles about it between 1976 and 1980, and also co-authored an influential Savant Institute report on it with James Martin.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Over the next few years, Finkelstein continued work in a more business-driven direction, which was intended to address a rapidly changing business environment; Martin continued work in a more data processing-driven direction.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Richter, guided by Clive Finkelstein, played a significant role in revamping IEM as well as helping to design the IEM software product (user data), which helped automate IEM.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] In the early 2000s, the data and data tooling was generally held by the information technology (IT) teams in most companies.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Other teams then used data for their work (e.g. reporting), and there was usually little overlap in data skillset between these parts of the business.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] In the early 2010s, with the rise of the internet, the massive increase in data volumes, velocity, and variety led to the term big data to describe the data itself, and data-driven tech companies like Facebook and Airbnb started using the phrase **data engineer**.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Due to the new scale of the data, major firms like Google, Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Microsoft, and Netflix started to move away from traditional ETL and storage techniques.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] They started creating **data engineering**, a type of software engineering focused on data, and in particular infrastructure, warehousing, data protection, cybersecurity, mining, modelling, processing, and metadata management.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] This change in approach was particularly focused on cloud computing.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Data started to be handled and used by many parts of the business, such as sales and marketing, and not just IT.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] High-performance computing is critical for the processing and analysis of data.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] One particularly widespread approach to computing for data engineering is dataflow programming, in which the computation is represented as a directed graph (dataflow graph); nodes are the operations, and edges represent the flow of data.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Popular implementations include Apache Spark, and the deep learning specific TensorFlow.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] More recent implementations, such as Differential/Timely Dataflow, have used incremental computing for much more efficient data processing.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Data is stored in a variety of ways, one of the key deciding factors is in how the data will be used.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Data engineers optimize data storage and processing systems to reduce costs.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] They use data compression, partitioning, and archiving.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] If the data is structured and some form of online transaction processing is required, then databases are generally used.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Originally mostly relational databases were used, with strong ACID transaction correctness guarantees; most relational databases use SQL for their queries.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] However, with the growth of data in the 2010s, NoSQL databases have also become popular since they horizontally scaled more easily than relational databases by giving up the ACID transaction guarantees, as well as reducing the object-relational impedance mismatch.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] More recently, NewSQL databases — which attempt to allow horizontal scaling while retaining ACID guarantees — have become popular.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] If the data is structured and online analytical processing is required (but not online transaction processing), then data warehouses are a main choice.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] They enable data analysis, mining, and artificial intelligence on a much larger scale than databases can allow, and indeed data often flow from databases into data warehouses.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Business analysts, data engineers, and data scientists can access data warehouses using tools such as SQL or business intelligence software.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] A data lake is a centralized repository for storing, processing, and securing large volumes of data.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] A data lake can contain structured data from relational databases, semi-structured data, unstructured data, and binary data.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] A data lake can be created on premises or in a cloud-based environment using the services from public cloud vendors such as Amazon, Microsoft, or Google.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] If the data is less structured, then often they are just stored as files.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] The number and variety of different data processes and storage locations can become overwhelming for users.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] This inspired the usage of a workflow management system (e.g.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Airflow) to allow the data tasks to be specified, created, and monitored.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] The tasks are often specified as a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Business objectives that executives set for what's to come are characterized in key business plans, with their more noteworthy definition in tactical business plans and implementation in operational business plans.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Most businesses today recognize the fundamental need to grow a business plan that follows this strategy.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] It is often difficult to implement these plans because of the lack of transparency at the tactical and operational degrees of organizations.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] This kind of planning requires feedback to allow for early correction of problems that are due to miscommunication and misinterpretation of the business plan.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] The design of data systems involves several components such as architecting data platforms, and designing data stores.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Data modeling is the process of producing a data model, an abstract model to describe the data and relationships between different parts of the data.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] A **data engineer** is a type of software engineer who creates big data ETL pipelines to manage the flow of data through the organization.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] This makes it possible to take huge amounts of data and translate it into insights.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] They are focused on the production readiness of data and things like formats, resilience, scaling, and security.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] Data engineers usually hail from a software engineering background and are proficient in programming languages like Java, Python, Scala, and Rust.
[src:databricks/data-engineering] They will be more familiar with databases, architecture, cloud computing, and Agile software development.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] A **data lake** is a system or repository of data stored in its natural, raw format, usually object blobs or files.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] A data lake is usually a single store of data including raw copies of source system data, sensor data, social data etc., and transformed data used for tasks such as reporting, visualization, advanced analytics, and machine learning.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] A data lake can include structured data from relational databases (rows and columns), semi-structured data (CSV, logs, XML, JSON), unstructured data (emails, documents, PDFs), and binary data (images, audio, video).
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] A data lake can be established *on premises* (within an organization's data centers) or *in the cloud* (using cloud services).
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] James Dixon, then chief technology officer at Pentaho, coined the term by 2011 to contrast it with data mart, which is a smaller repository of interesting attributes derived from raw data.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] In promoting data lakes, he argued that data marts have several inherent problems, such as information siloing.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) said that data lakes could "put an end to data silos".
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] Many companies use cloud storage services such as Google Cloud Storage and Amazon S3 or a distributed file system such as Apache Hadoop distributed file system (HDFS).
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] There is a gradual academic interest in the concept of data lakes.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] For example, Personal DataLake at Cardiff University is a new type of data lake which aims at managing big data of individual users by providing a single point of collecting, organizing, and sharing personal data.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] Early data lakes, such as Hadoop 1.0, had limited capabilities because it only supported batch-oriented processing (Map Reduce).
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] Interacting with it required expertise in Java, map reduce and higher-level tools like Apache Pig, Apache Spark and Apache Hive (which were also originally batch-oriented).
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] Poorly managed data lakes have been facetiously called data swamps.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] In June 2015, David Needle characterized "so-called data lakes" as "one of the more controversial ways to manage big data".
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] PwC was also careful to note in their research that not all data lake initiatives are successful.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] They describe companies that build successful data lakes as gradually maturing their lake as they figure out which data and metadata are important to the organization.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] Another criticism is that the term *data lake* is used with many different meanings.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] It may be used to refer to, for example: any tools or data management practices that are not data warehouses; a particular technology for implementation; a raw data reservoir; a hub for ETL offload; or a central hub for self-service analytics.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] While critiques of data lakes are warranted, in many cases they apply to other data projects as well.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] For example, the definition of *data warehouse* is also changeable, and not all data warehouse efforts have been successful.
[src:databricks/data-lakehouse] In response to various critiques, McKinsey noted that the data lake should be viewed as a service model for delivering business value within the enterprise, not a technology outcome.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks developed the 'data lakehouse' architecture, which combines elements of data warehouses and data lakes for managing structured and unstructured data.
[src:databricks/databricks] The company develops Delta Lake, an open-source project that adds ACID transaction support to data lakes.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks' platform incorporates the company's core data and AI offerings, including the Lakebase database designed for AI agents, Lakeflow Designer for building data pipelines, and the Agent Bricks production-scale AI agent development workspace.
[src:databricks/databricks] The company recently announced Genie Code, an autonomous AI agent that assists with data engineering, data science and analytics tasks.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks grew out of the AMPLab project at University of California, Berkeley, that was involved in making Apache Spark, an open-source distributed computing framework built atop Scala.
[src:databricks/databricks] The company was founded by Ali Ghodsi, Andy Konwinski, Arsalan Tavakoli-Shiraji, Ion Stoica, Matei Zaharia, Patrick Wendell, and Reynold Xin.
[src:databricks/databricks] Microsoft Azure integrated Databricks as Azure Databricks in 2017.
[src:databricks/databricks] In February 2021, together with Google Cloud, Databricks provided integration with the Google Kubernetes Engine and Google's BigQuery platform.
[src:databricks/databricks] In February 2021, the company reported having more than 5,000 customers.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks announced the Data Intelligence Platform, integrating its lakehouse architecture with generative AI capabilities acquired from MosaicML.
[src:databricks/databricks] The firm was valued at $62 billion in December 2024, following a $10 billion funding round.
[src:databricks/databricks] In early March 2025, Databricks announced it would invest $1 billion in San Francisco's downtown.
[src:databricks/databricks] In March 2025, Databricks entered a five-year partnership with Anthropic, incorporating Anthropic's AI products into its platform in a deal valued at $100 million.
[src:databricks/databricks] In June 2025, Databricks entered into a four-year partnership with Alphabet to incorporate Gemini into the Databricks platform.
[src:databricks/databricks] The company launched Agent Bricks, a suite of tools to help organizations build AI agents, and Lakebase, an OLTP database.
[src:databricks/databricks] In April 2025, Databricks was featured in the Forbes AI 50 list.
[src:databricks/databricks] In September 2025, Databricks entered into a partnership with OpenAI to incorporate the company's LLMs into the Databricks platform in a deal valued at $100 million.
[src:databricks/databricks] In December 2025, Databricks raised more than $4 billion in a Series L funding round at a $134 billion valuation.
[src:databricks/databricks] This was Databricks' third major fundraise in less than a year.
[src:databricks/databricks] In June 2020, Databricks bought Redash, an open-source tool for data visualization and building of interactive dashboards.
[src:databricks/databricks] In 2021, it bought German no-code company 8080 Labs whose product, bamboolib, allowed data exploration without any coding.
[src:databricks/databricks] In May 2023, Databricks bought data security group Okera, extending Databricks data governance capabilities.
[src:databricks/databricks] In June, it bought the open-source generative AI startup MosaicML for $1.4 billion.
[src:databricks/databricks] In October, Databricks bought data replication startup Arcion for $100 million.
[src:databricks/databricks] In 2024, Databricks bought data-management startup Tabular for over $1 billion.
[src:databricks/databricks] In March 2023, in response to the popularity of OpenAI's ChatGPT, the company introduced an open-source language model, named Dolly after Dolly the sheep, that developers could use to create custom chatbots.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks claimed that Dolly had "ChatGPT-like instruction following ability", but has not released formal benchmark tests comparing it to ChatGPT.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks reported $1.6 billion in revenue for the 2023 fiscal year.
[src:databricks/databricks] In 2025, Databricks acquired a serverless database startup, Neon, for around $1 billion.
[src:databricks/databricks] In September 2013, Databricks announced it raised $13.9 million from Andreessen Horowitz and said it aimed to offer an alternative to Google's MapReduce system.
[src:databricks/databricks] Microsoft was a noted investor of Databricks in 2019, participating in the company's Series E at an unspecified amount.
[src:databricks/databricks] The company has raised $1.9 billion in funding, including a $1 billion Series G led by Franklin Templeton at a $28 billion post-money valuation in February 2021.
[src:databricks/databricks] Other investors include Amazon Web Services, CapitalG (a growth equity firm under Alphabet Inc.) and Salesforce Ventures.
[src:databricks/databricks] In August 2021, Databricks finished its eighth round of funding by raising $1.6 billion and valuing the company at $38 billion.
[src:databricks/databricks] In December 2024, Databricks announced a $10 billion financing at a valuation of $62 billion.
[src:databricks/databricks] In August 2025, Databricks announced a $1 billion Series K funding round, raising their valuation to over $100 billion.
[src:databricks/databricks] Just 3 months later, in December 2025, Databricks completed a $4 billion Series L funding round at a new valuation of $134 billion.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks develops a cloud data platform referred to as a 'lakehouse', combining features of data warehouses and data lakes.
[src:databricks/databricks] Unlike traditional proprietary data warehouses, the Databricks architecture processes data while allowing organizations to retain the underlying files in their own cloud storage using open-source formats like Apache Iceberg and Delta Lake.
[src:databricks/databricks] Industry analysts note this separation of compute and storage mitigates vendor lock-in and avoids proprietary data egress fees.
[src:databricks/databricks] The platform is built on the open-source Apache Spark framework, enabling analytical queries on semi-structured data without requiring a traditional database schema.
[src:databricks/databricks] While the platform's classic architecture provided robust distributed computing capabilities, it inherently required data teams to manually configure, size, and manage the underlying cluster infrastructure.
[src:databricks/databricks] To eliminate this operational complexity, Databricks introduced a serverless architecture across its analytics and AI workloads.
[src:databricks/databricks] This serverless tier fully abstracts the cloud environment, automatically provisioning, scaling, and terminating compute resources without requiring manual tuning or cluster management.
[src:databricks/databricks] In October 2022, Lakehouse received FedRAMP authorization for use with the U.S. federal government and contractors.
[src:databricks/databricks] The company has also created Delta Lake, MLflow and Koalas, open source projects that span data engineering, data science and machine learning.
[src:databricks/databricks] In June 2020, Databricks launched Delta Engine, a fast query engine for Delta Lake, compatible with Apache Spark and MLflow.
[src:databricks/databricks] In November 2020, Databricks introduced Databricks SQL (previously called SQL Analytics) for running business intelligence and analytics reporting on top of data lakes.
[src:databricks/databricks] Analysts can query data sets with standard SQL or use connectors to integrate with business intelligence tools like Holistics, Tableau, Qlik, Sigma, Looker, and ThoughtSpot.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks offers a platform for other workloads, including machine learning, data storage and processing, streaming analytics, and business intelligence.
[src:databricks/databricks] In early 2024, Databricks released the Mosaic set of tools for customizing, fine-tuning and building AI systems.
[src:databricks/databricks] It includes AI Vector Search for building RAG models; AI Model Serving, a service for deploying, governing, querying and monitoring models fine-tuned or pre-deployed by Databricks; and AI Pretraining, a platform for enterprises to create their own LLMs.
[src:databricks/databricks] In March 2024, Databricks released its DBRX foundation model under the Databricks Open Model License.
[src:databricks/databricks] It has a mixture-of-experts architecture and is built on the MegaBlocks open-source project.
[src:databricks/databricks] According to the company, DBRX performed competitively on industry benchmarks against other open-source models available at the time.
[src:databricks/databricks] It beat other models like Llama 2 at solving logic puzzles and answering general knowledge questions, among other tasks.
[src:databricks/databricks] While it has 136 billion parameters, it only uses 36 billion, on average, to generate outputs.
[src:databricks/databricks] According to Databricks, DBRX can be used as a foundation for companies to build customized AI models using their proprietary data.
[src:databricks/databricks] In June 2024, Databricks open sourced Unity Catalog, a unified governance offering, under the Apache Spark 2.0 license.
[src:databricks/databricks] In addition to building the Databricks platform, the company has co-organized massive open online courses about Spark and a conference for the Spark community called the Data + AI Summit, formerly known as Spark Summit.
[src:databricks/databricks] At the 2025 Data + AI Summit, Databricks introduced Agent Bricks, a development platform for AI agents, Lakebase, a transactional database, and Databricks One, a no-code AI business intelligence platform.
[src:databricks/databricks] The company also disclosed its Databricks SQL product would grow to a $1 billion revenue run rate.
[src:databricks/databricks] In March 2026, Databricks released Genie Code, an AI agent for data science and engineering tasks.
[src:databricks/databricks] That same month, the company announced Lakewatch, an AI-powered agentic security platform to automate threat detection and response.
[src:databricks/databricks] As of February 9, 2026, Databricks had a $5.4 billion revenue run rate, growing > 65% year over year.
[src:databricks/databricks] Databricks also delivered positive free cash flow over the 12 months prior.
[src:databricks/databricks] As of June 16, 2026, CNBC reported that Databricks' annualized revenue reached $6.9 billion, representing an 80% year-over-year growth.
[src:databricks/databricks] In December 2024, Databricks along with Wiz and Workday has decided to run their products on top of AWS via the new button called "Buy with AWS".
[src:databricks/databricks] In June 2025, Databricks announced a partnership with Google Cloud to integrate its platform with Google Cloud services.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:databricks/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
